00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.160
MALE SPEAKER: Jen, over to you.

00:00:01.160 --> 00:00:02.618
JENNIFER EVANS:
OK, well, thank you

00:00:02.618 --> 00:00:05.280
very much for coming and
spending your lunch hour

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:08.090
listening to me talk about
something quite random.

00:00:08.090 --> 00:00:10.360
I'm a senior lecturer in
history at the University

00:00:10.360 --> 00:00:11.530
of Hertfordshire.

00:00:11.530 --> 00:00:14.009
And I run a blog called
Early Modern Medicine.

00:00:14.009 --> 00:00:15.300
I have some cards at the front.

00:00:15.300 --> 00:00:17.670
If you do you find yourself
fascinated by the end,

00:00:17.670 --> 00:00:19.340
please come and take one.

00:00:19.340 --> 00:00:22.840
And I'm going to talk to
you about my first book.

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:25.170
As you'll have seen from
your raffle tickets,

00:00:25.170 --> 00:00:27.660
academic monograph,
slightly different ballgame,

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:30.080
very expensive, so
there's only a few of them

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:33.260
here, and slightly
different process, maybe,

00:00:33.260 --> 00:00:35.690
to writing other kinds of books.

00:00:35.690 --> 00:00:38.730
So what I'm going to do is
try and condense my book

00:00:38.730 --> 00:00:42.950
into 50 minutes, give
you the major highlights.

00:00:42.950 --> 00:00:44.980
And what I really
hope to show you

00:00:44.980 --> 00:00:49.400
is that we tend to think in
modern society of aphrodisiacs

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:50.757
in a very specific way.

00:00:50.757 --> 00:00:52.590
You say the word
"aphrodisiac," and everyone

00:00:52.590 --> 00:00:55.340
thinks about lust,
sexual desire,

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:59.030
and we very rarely think about
it in relation to reproduction.

00:00:59.030 --> 00:01:01.220
And what I want to
show you is that what

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:02.960
I found while
reading 17th century

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:06.680
medical texts is that
wasn't the case in the past.

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:08.800
And actually, when you
read a lot of history books

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:11.220
on this subject,
historians will tend

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:14.149
to just talk about aphrodisiacs
using modern technology.

00:01:14.149 --> 00:01:15.690
But they're not
quite the same thing.

00:01:15.690 --> 00:01:17.360
They're must more of a medicine.

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:19.250
So hopefully that's
what we're going

00:01:19.250 --> 00:01:22.980
to get to over the
next 45, 50 minutes.

00:01:22.980 --> 00:01:26.820
So before I get on to that, I
wanted to cover some background

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:28.005
material.

00:01:28.005 --> 00:01:29.930
I wasn't quite sure
what kind of a crowd

00:01:29.930 --> 00:01:33.170
I'd be talking to in terms
of historical interest

00:01:33.170 --> 00:01:37.610
or enthusiasm or knowledge,
so a few little things.

00:01:37.610 --> 00:01:41.300
I'm going to bandy the term
"early modern" quite a lot.

00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:44.010
Historians do this all the
time, and then people say, oh,

00:01:44.010 --> 00:01:45.890
is that the medieval period?

00:01:45.890 --> 00:01:47.030
No, it's not.

00:01:47.030 --> 00:01:53.270
So we're normally talking about
the area between 1550 and 1750

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:56.690
or between 1500 and 1750.

00:01:56.690 --> 00:01:58.440
What I'm going to talk
to you about today,

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:01.910
I mostly focus on
1550 and after.

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:03.300
And there's no exciting reason.

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:06.720
It's just very pragmatic in
that medical books before 1550

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:08.490
tended to be published in Latin.

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:10.170
I don't read Latin,
so my book would

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:13.099
have been really short had
I tried to go before that.

00:02:13.099 --> 00:02:15.140
I do sometimes read stuff
that's older than that,

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:19.490
but I tend to stick with things
that are written in English.

00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:22.860
Predominantly, my main interest
is in the 17th century.

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:25.470
And this is because I think
it's the most exciting and most

00:02:25.470 --> 00:02:27.090
vibrant century
you could possibly

00:02:27.090 --> 00:02:28.650
study for English history.

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:30.780
As many of you
will probably know,

00:02:30.780 --> 00:02:32.450
it's the era of the
English civil wars.

00:02:32.450 --> 00:02:34.370
It's the era of
the protectorates,

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:38.310
the regicide of Charles I,
Restoration of Charles II.

00:02:38.310 --> 00:02:41.380
It's the era of the
Glorious Revolution in 1684

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:44.490
when James II is ousted
and the Protestant William

00:02:44.490 --> 00:02:47.220
of Orange and his wife
Mary are given the throne.

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:50.150
But it's also really
interesting outside of politics.

00:02:50.150 --> 00:02:52.830
I'm not a big fan of
political history.

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:55.890
In the world of science,
a lot of the names

00:02:55.890 --> 00:02:59.030
that you'll have learned
at GCSE and earlier,

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:01.570
they're all people working in
the 17th century, so Robert

00:03:01.570 --> 00:03:04.979
Boyle, Robert Hook, Christopher
Wren, Francis Bacon,

00:03:04.979 --> 00:03:07.020
and perhaps the most famous
of all, Isaac Newton.

00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:10.650
They're all 17th century
men who like to study.

00:03:10.650 --> 00:03:12.590
And in the world
of medicine, it's

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:14.340
also a really important era.

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:16.230
There was a lot happening.

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:19.550
William Harvey discovered
the circulation of the blood

00:03:19.550 --> 00:03:22.740
and published his first
book on that in 1628.

00:03:22.740 --> 00:03:24.490
And perhaps more
important for what

00:03:24.490 --> 00:03:26.870
I'm going to talk about today,
both the egg and the sperm

00:03:26.870 --> 00:03:29.130
were discovered in
the 17th century.

00:03:29.130 --> 00:03:32.650
So there's a lot happening
in 17th century England.

00:03:32.650 --> 00:03:36.170
And the other background
I want to briefly cover

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:38.870
is the medical
model of the time.

00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:40.370
Most people will
have heard of this.

00:03:40.370 --> 00:03:43.580
Hands up if you've heard
of the humoral model.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:44.260
Excellent.

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:46.690
Hands up if you
know what it means.

00:03:46.690 --> 00:03:49.060
Oh, good, so my next
slide isn't pointless.

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:52.320
OK, so humoral medicine
is the predominant way

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:54.690
of thinking about the
body in the 17th century.

00:03:54.690 --> 00:03:57.770
And it's what we're
going to focus on today.

00:03:57.770 --> 00:03:59.270
That's not to say
new things weren't

00:03:59.270 --> 00:04:00.560
happening in the 17th century.

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:02.240
You get the rise of
chemical medicine

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:05.230
very early in the century, and
towards the end of the century

00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:07.500
you get a focus on
nervous disorders.

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:10.030
Everything becomes about
nerves and mechanics.

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:13.220
But predominantly, people
focused on the humoral model.

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:14.860
And this was a
very ancient model

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:18.730
created by Hippocrates,
who lived around circa 460

00:04:18.730 --> 00:04:20.839
to 370 BCE.

00:04:20.839 --> 00:04:25.570
And it was refined then in the
second century AD by Galen.

00:04:25.570 --> 00:04:29.250
The theories had existed
throughout the medieval period.

00:04:29.250 --> 00:04:30.300
They were there.

00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:33.400
But really in the Renaissance
in the 16th century,

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:35.440
there's like a
drive to rediscover

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:38.020
that ancient medicine
and to revive the text

00:04:38.020 --> 00:04:42.100
and to understand what
Hippocrates and Galen said

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:43.520
in its purest form.

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:47.980
So humoral medicine has
this kind of resurgence.

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:49.935
Older historians--
and I don't mean age;

00:04:49.935 --> 00:04:51.920
I'm talking
chronologically-- tend

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:54.790
to say that the humoral
model stops being influential

00:04:54.790 --> 00:04:56.760
at the end of the 17th century.

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.050
For what I look at,
reproductive medicine,

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:01.040
that's not really the case.

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:03.520
And more and more
historians are accepting

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:05.350
that actually the
humoral model stays

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:07.630
quite influential
through the 18th century

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:10.840
and even tailing into
the 19th century.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:12.970
So how does the
humoral model work?

00:05:12.970 --> 00:05:15.150
I'm hoping everyone
can see this slide.

00:05:15.150 --> 00:05:18.180
So under the humoral
model, your body

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:20.920
is created, or
predominantly made up,

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:25.160
of four humors, or
fluids-- blood, phlegm,

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:27.340
yellow bile, and black bile.

00:05:27.340 --> 00:05:30.410
And each of those
four fluids exists

00:05:30.410 --> 00:05:33.930
inside your body in
your own personalized

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:35.397
kind of complexion.

00:05:35.397 --> 00:05:36.980
So some people have
more of one thing.

00:05:36.980 --> 00:05:39.080
Some people have more
of another thing.

00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:42.434
And those humors are all
related to different kinds

00:05:42.434 --> 00:05:42.975
of qualities.

00:05:42.975 --> 00:05:46.970
So each humor has a quality--
hot, cold, wet, and dry.

00:05:46.970 --> 00:05:49.962
And again, that affects
what kind of body you have.

00:05:49.962 --> 00:05:52.170
And what's really interesting
about the humoral model

00:05:52.170 --> 00:05:55.149
is that-- you might
say unlike today,

00:05:55.149 --> 00:05:56.440
but that might not be the case.

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:59.414
Unlike today, your
humoral complexion,

00:05:59.414 --> 00:06:01.080
the way your body is
made up, is thought

00:06:01.080 --> 00:06:02.830
to affect everything about you.

00:06:02.830 --> 00:06:04.950
So your strength,
your character,

00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:07.460
your emotional
stability, the kinds

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:09.440
of diseases you're
liable to get are all

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:12.010
linked to your
humoral complexion.

00:06:12.010 --> 00:06:14.680
And I really like this.

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:19.470
You can see the picture
on the right-hang side

00:06:19.470 --> 00:06:24.000
to you shows four different
types of body-- phlegmatic,

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.460
sanguine, melancholic,
and choleric.

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:31.220
And you can see on
the left-hand side

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:33.400
is a womanly body, because
women are thought to be

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:35.699
colder and more moist than men.

00:06:35.699 --> 00:06:36.990
Men are on the right-hand side.

00:06:36.990 --> 00:06:38.710
They're hotter and drier.

00:06:38.710 --> 00:06:42.070
And this, in the humoral model,
is more perfect, so patriarchy

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:44.010
built into the medical model.

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.460
Women are just
less good than men.

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:50.362
So this all effects the kind
of person you're liable to be.

00:06:50.362 --> 00:06:51.820
And these are
another set of images

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:54.900
showing the different kinds
of person you might be.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:57.500
And my favorite book
for describing this

00:06:57.500 --> 00:07:01.060
was one written by John Fage,
and he really nicely sums up

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:02.790
how these different
humoral complexions

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:04.570
affect your personality.

00:07:04.570 --> 00:07:11.390
So he writes that choleric men
were for the most part short

00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:15.180
because their natural
heat consumes and dries up

00:07:15.180 --> 00:07:17.900
all the moisture in their
body so they can't grow.

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:20.250
And this, he said, was
connected to the fact

00:07:20.250 --> 00:07:23.210
that they would
sooner grow beards,

00:07:23.210 --> 00:07:25.680
they would be
naturally quick-witted,

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:28.370
they would be courageous
and have strong appetites.

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:30.030
Unfortunately for
choleric men, they're

00:07:30.030 --> 00:07:33.370
also liable to be arrogant,
graceless, quarrelsome,

00:07:33.370 --> 00:07:36.470
fraudulent, and
constant and crafty.

00:07:36.470 --> 00:07:41.227
Whereas, he says,
phlegmatic men-- and I'm

00:07:41.227 --> 00:07:43.060
sure I don't need to
explain what phlegm is.

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:47.680
It's still pretty much the same,
cold, wet, goopy, grossness.

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:51.050
Phlegmatic men are hindered
by their bodies' overabundance

00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:52.080
of phlegm.

00:07:52.080 --> 00:07:54.020
And so they're likely
to be short, gross,

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:58.250
and fat without hair or beards,
and so they're not very manly.

00:07:58.250 --> 00:08:01.080
And they're also liable to be
slothful, forgetful, cowardly,

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:02.710
covetous, and vain.

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:04.140
So everything about
you is kind of

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:08.370
dictated by the makeup of
your body and these fluids.

00:08:08.370 --> 00:08:10.130
And importantly
under this model,

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:12.590
a healthy body is
a body that flows.

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:14.010
because it is made of fluids.

00:08:14.010 --> 00:08:16.820
And a healthy body is
one that's in balance.

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:20.050
So you should be maintaining
your own balance of humors

00:08:20.050 --> 00:08:21.807
in order to maintain
your health.

00:08:21.807 --> 00:08:24.140
And they do this through
something called regimen, which

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:26.710
again was something taken
from Hippocrates and Galen,

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:28.700
and it's focused
around something

00:08:28.700 --> 00:08:32.929
they call the Six Non-Naturals,
six factors that you regulate

00:08:32.929 --> 00:08:34.710
in order to maintain health.

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:38.330
And I am going to read these off
my list-- air, diet, exercise,

00:08:38.330 --> 00:08:42.789
bodily evacuations of all
kinds, emotions, and sleep.

00:08:42.789 --> 00:08:45.930
And if you regulate those,
you should be very healthy.

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:48.230
And perhaps the
most famous thing

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:49.850
about humoral
medicine is connected

00:08:49.850 --> 00:08:51.920
to this idea of
balance and flow,

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:53.985
is the way in which
they treat illness.

00:08:53.985 --> 00:08:57.100
So illness tends to
be a buildup of one

00:08:57.100 --> 00:09:00.750
humor in the body, or an
excess, and the only way

00:09:00.750 --> 00:09:03.690
to kill that is to
remove the excess.

00:09:03.690 --> 00:09:06.800
And so early modern
medicine and before

00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:10.750
tends to focus a lot on purging
and lots of emetics next

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:14.130
to make you vomit, things
to go the other way as well,

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:18.450
and the most famous, phlebotomy,
so cutting with scalpel

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:21.840
or using leeches to
remove excess blood.

00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:23.566
And so we all look
back on the past

00:09:23.566 --> 00:09:25.190
and think, oh, my
God, that's horrific,

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:26.997
what are they doing
to these people,

00:09:26.997 --> 00:09:29.580
it actually makes perfect sense
for what they're trying to do.

00:09:29.580 --> 00:09:31.810
They're trying to
restore balance.

00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:34.430
So it was under
this type of model

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:36.310
that the people I'm
looking at tried

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:40.670
to understand aphrodisiacs
and how they worked.

00:09:40.670 --> 00:09:43.820
So before I really get into
the kind of meat of the book,

00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:48.270
I want to have a little section
of caveats and addendums.

00:09:48.270 --> 00:09:50.420
And the first is
that you are going

00:09:50.420 --> 00:09:53.211
to hear about some quite
famous, well-known aphrodisiacs.

00:09:53.211 --> 00:09:54.960
Oysters in particular
are going to pop up,

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:57.270
and asparagus and
a couple of others.

00:09:57.270 --> 00:10:00.290
But you're about to be bombarded
with the most ludicrously,

00:10:00.290 --> 00:10:03.647
ridiculously long list of foods
that function as aphrodisiacs.

00:10:03.647 --> 00:10:05.480
Please don't leave here
and worry about what

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:06.830
you're going to have for lunch.

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:09.380
It's fine.

00:10:09.380 --> 00:10:10.757
The major caveat
is I'm not going

00:10:10.757 --> 00:10:12.590
to be talking about
chocolate, so anyone who

00:10:12.590 --> 00:10:14.589
was here hoping for a
nice history of chocolate,

00:10:14.589 --> 00:10:15.700
I'm very sorry.

00:10:15.700 --> 00:10:17.580
I didn't talk about
chocolate in the book

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:20.540
because it's everybody's
favorite go-to aphrodisiac

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:24.310
substance, so there are hundreds
of histories of chocolate.

00:10:24.310 --> 00:10:26.270
The other reason I didn't
write about chocolate

00:10:26.270 --> 00:10:29.520
explicitly is because,
as hopefully you'll see,

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:31.970
chocolate is one of the
most famous aphrodisiacs

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:33.070
in the 17th century.

00:10:33.070 --> 00:10:34.950
Everyone knows chocolate
is an aphrodisiac.

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:36.450
But they're talking
about the drink,

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:38.310
very different to
what we know today.

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:41.930
It's a mix of cocoa, milk,
spices, often chili and pepper

00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:42.695
and cinnamon.

00:10:42.695 --> 00:10:44.570
And the reason I'm not
going to talk about it

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:48.370
is because it's seen as
luxurious and exotic,

00:10:48.370 --> 00:10:50.130
and so the chocolate
is an aphrodisiac,

00:10:50.130 --> 00:10:52.635
but it's also what goes in it
that makes it an aphrodisiac.

00:10:52.635 --> 00:10:56.100
And not everyone's sure
what is more important,

00:10:56.100 --> 00:10:57.490
the cocoa or everything else.

00:10:57.490 --> 00:11:01.370
And we're going to talk
about the everything else.

00:11:01.370 --> 00:11:05.470
The other kind of brief
caveat I want to make

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:10.110
is an apology for the quotes.

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:12.430
If you don't understand
something I'm quoting,

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:15.770
please just wave at me and
we'll stop and talk about it.

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:18.990
So to think a little bit
about reproduction and sex

00:11:18.990 --> 00:11:21.619
in the early modern
era, as I said

00:11:21.619 --> 00:11:23.160
at the very beginning,
what we really

00:11:23.160 --> 00:11:25.140
need to do for the
next 20 minutes or so

00:11:25.140 --> 00:11:27.700
is throw out your
modern understanding

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:30.690
in how we think about
sex in the modern day.

00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:35.950
In this era, reproduction is
almost inextricably linked

00:11:35.950 --> 00:11:38.010
